on": "TGF-b", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.98903489112854, "span": {"begin": 1552, "end": 1557}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:26284"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ERa", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9679226279258728, "span": {"begin": 1616, "end": 1619}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MCF-7 cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.7339897155761719, "span": {"begin": 1634, "end": 1645}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7040"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TGF-b", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.975520133972168, "span": {"begin": 1668, "end": 1673}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992063045501709, "span": {"begin": 1686, "end": 1694}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MCF-7 cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.7736344337463379, "span": {"begin": 1705, "end": 1716}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4087"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Smad2/3", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9976832866668701, "span": {"begin": 1718, "end": 1725}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:57154"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Smad-selective E3 ubiquitin ligase", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9469494223594666, "span": {"begin": 1734, "end": 1768}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:57154"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Smurf", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9831488132476807, "span": {"begin": 1769, "end": 1774}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:26284"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ERa", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9803747534751892, "span": {"begin": 1805, "end": 1808}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4086"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Smad proteins", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9744412899017334, "span": {"begin": 1856, "end": 1869}}], "text": "E2/ERa signalling, in part through transcriptional activation of luminal/epithelial-related transcription factors, promotes the development of mammary epithelia along a luminal/epithelial lineage. GATA3 and ERa both promote each other (Eeckhoute et al.,2007). In normal breast epithelia, GATA3 is needed for luminal differentiation(Kouros-Mehr et al.,2008)&nbsp;and GATA3 and ERa control many of the same genes (Wilson et al.,2008). &nbsp;In mice, forcing GATA3 expression in mesenchymal breast cancer cells produces mesenchymal&ndash;epithelial transition (MET), a reversible mechanism analogous to EMT, and prevents tumour metastasis (Yan et al.,2010). Another ERa-interacting transcription factor, FOXA1, is essential for luminal lineage in mammary epithelia and stimulates ductal development in mice (Bernardo et al.,2010). FOXA1 enhances ERa gene expression by increasing the accessibility of estrogen-response regions for ERa binding (Nakshatri et al.,&nbsp;2009). In breast cancer cells, on the other hand, E2 appears to increase FOXA1 expression. Importantly, ERa, FOXA1, and GATA3 are all positive breast cancer prognostic factors(Nakshatri et al.,2009).  ERa signalling enhances primary lesion formation (and therefore is mitogenic), but it can control the EMT process (and thus is anti-metastatic) up to a point. Signaling pathways that lead to EMT are antagonised by E2/ERa signalling. TGF-b, for example, has been demonstrated to generate EMT in human mammary epithelial cells, and overexpression of the EMT-inducing protein Snail boosted TGF-b signalling and invasiveness while decreasing adhesion and ERa expression in MCF-7 cells (Taylor et al.,2010). TGF-b has an anti-estrogen impact on MCF-7 cells. Smad2/3 and the Smad-selective E3 ubiquitin ligase Smurf create a ternary complex with ERa, which enhances the proteosomal degradation of Smad proteins, according to Ito et al (Ito et al.,2010).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:44:41 +0000 2026"}